      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        MDR: Motor Driven Roller Conveyors
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>An MDR (Motor Driven Roller) conveyor uses small 24VDC brushless DC motors built inside individual conveyor rollers to create independently controlled zones for product transport and zero-pressure accumulation. MDR technology has become the dominant powered roller platform for new conveyor installations in distribution, fulfillment, and <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">packaging line</a> applications because it eliminates external motors, belts, chains, and compressed air while reducing energy consumption by 50% or more compared to conventional <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/powered/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">powered roller conveyors</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- How MDR Works -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="how-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Technical Deep-Dive</div>
      <h2 id="how-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        How MDR Technology <span class="text-accent">Works</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">The Motorized Roller</h3>
        <p>An MDR roller looks identical to a standard conveyor roller from the outside , a steel or aluminum tube with bearings and axles. Inside, a compact brushless DC (BLDC) motor and planetary gearbox convert 24VDC power into roller rotation. The motor stator mounts to the fixed axle. The rotor drives the outer roller tube. No external gearmotor, belt, or chain exists. The entire drive system fits inside a standard 1.9" or 2.0" diameter roller tube.</p>
        <p><a href="https://www.interroll.com/products/conveyors-sorters/roller-drives/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Interroll's RollerDrive</a> EC5000 series, Itoh Denki's PM600 series, and Rulmeca's RDR series are the three leading MDR roller platforms. These rollers deliver 0.3-2.5 Nm of torque at speeds from 0.1 to 1.2 m/s (approximately 20-230 FPM). Power consumption per roller is typically 10-50 watts , a fraction of the power consumed by a conventional gearmotor driving an entire conveyor section.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Interroll EC5000 torque and speed range specs -->

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Zone Architecture</h3>
        <p>Each MDR zone consists of four components: one motorized roller, 2-4 slave rollers (connected to the motor roller by polyurethane O-ring bands), one photo-eye sensor, and one zone controller card. The zone controller reads the sensor, communicates with adjacent zone controllers via a simple signal wire, and controls the motor roller's speed and direction.</p>
        <p>Zone length matches the product length plus a gap. A zone for 24" cases is typically 30" long (24" case + 6" gap). A zone for 12" cartons is typically 18" long. Each zone operates independently , running, stopped, or reversing , regardless of what adjacent zones are doing. This independent zone control is the foundation of <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">zero-pressure accumulation</a>.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Zero-Pressure Accumulation Logic</h3>
        <p>MDR ZPA uses a cascading signal protocol between zones. Each zone has three states: empty (no product detected), occupied-and-running (product present, downstream clear), and occupied-and-stopped (product present, downstream occupied). When a zone detects "downstream occupied," it stops its motor. The product stops in that zone with a controlled gap to the product ahead. This signal cascades upstream, filling zones back-to-front with gaps between every product.</p>
        <p>When the downstream blockage clears, the leading zone starts first, creating a gap. The next zone starts, and the release cascades upstream. This provides smooth, sequential product release , sometimes called "first-in, first-out" (FIFO) accumulation.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">24VDC Power Distribution</h3>
        <p>MDR systems use 24VDC power, distributed from a central power supply to each zone controller. The low voltage (24VDC is Class 2 / SELV) simplifies wiring , no conduit is required in most jurisdictions. Zone controllers draw 1-3 amps each. A single 24VDC power supply (typically 10-40 amps) serves 10-30 zones depending on load. The 24VDC architecture eliminates 480V/240V wiring to individual conveyor sections, reducing electrical installation cost significantly.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: NEC Class 2 wiring exemptions for 24VDC MDR installations -->
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

